          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Right Column - About Text -->
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
            I'm <strong class="text-white">Brandon van Vuuren</strong>, a full-stack developer and AI engineer who loves building 
            <strong class="text-blue-400">production-ready applications</strong> that actually work at scale. I get excited about 
            turning messy, complex requirements into clean systems that deliver real value to businesses and their users.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
            My bread and butter is the <strong class="text-white">modern JavaScript/TypeScript ecosystem</strong>. I work with 
            React, Next.js, and Node.js daily, backed by solid databases like PostgreSQL and MongoDB. From day one, I'm thinking 
            about performance, how things will scale, and whether the code will still make sense six months from now.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
            When it comes to <strong class="text-blue-400">AI and automation</strong>, I love fine-tuning language models for 
            specific use cases, building smart automation that cuts out tedious work, and deploying ML systems that fit naturally 
            into existing workflows. I'm all about practical AI that solves actual problems, not just flashy demos that look cool 
            but don't help anyone.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
            I've had the chance to work with startups and bigger companies across different industries. From real-time analytics 
            dashboards handling 10k+ events per second to custom LLM pipelines that cut training costs by 60%, every project teaches 
            me something new. My process is pretty straightforward: really understand what needs to happen, design something that'll 
            work, ship it quickly, and then improve it based on real feedback.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
